PART I. POPULATION TABLES.

AGES OF THE PEOPLE,

WITH THE

NUMBERS AND AGES OF MALES AND FEMALES IN EVERY COUNTY, PASTORAL DISTRICT, PROVINCE, ELECTORAL DISTRICT, TOWN, PARISH, AND VILLAGE IN THE COLONY.

POPULATION ENUMERATED 26TH APRIL, 1854.

LAID upon theCOUNCIL TABLEby theCOLONIAL SECRETARY,by commandof HIS EXCELLENCY THE LIEUTENANT GOVERNOR,and ordered by theCOUNCILto be printed, 21st March, 1855.

BY AUTHORITY:

JOIIN FERRES, GOVERNMENT PRINTER, MELBOURNE.

REPORT.

Registrar General's Office,

6th March, 1855.

SIR,

I have the honor to transmit herewith the returns of the population of Victoria, as ascertained by the Census taken on the 26th of April, 1854.

2.

It is much to be regretted that so much time has elapsed in their preparation, but the delay has been unavoidable. Many of the 45,880 schedules were almost as difficult to decipher as an Egyptian inscription ; not to mention the Chinese returns, for which recourse was had to a translator, and a laborious and careful revision of the whole was essential to the correctness of the abstracts. This important task has devolved upon an extremely limited staff, which, under existing circumstances, the Government has not felt itself justified in augmenting at an additional cost to the public ; nor indeed, as it turned out, would any such increase have materially expedited the period of submitting this report, inasmuch as the schedules for the City of Melbourne were not received from the Town Clerk's Office until the middle of December.

3.

The forms adopted in digesting the information contained in those schedules, have been, generally, those which the experience acquired in successive enumerations of the people in Great Britain led the Commissioners for taking the Census of 1851 to devise as best calculated to exhibit in a lucid and comprehensive manner, the numbers, ages, and condition of the inhabitants. It was, moreover, considered advisable, on this occasion, to comply with the expressed desire of scientific men at home, that the statistics of every part of the Empire should be drawn up on one uniform plan.

4.

The series of tables now presented, is designed to shew :—

  1. The population of the counties and of the pastoral districts, indicating the estimated area of each, and the quantity of Crown Lands which have been alienated.

  2. The population of the existing Electoral Districts.

  3. The population of the Electoral Provinces of the Legislative Council, as defined under the New Constitution Act.

  4. That of the Electoral Districts of the Legislative Assembly, as defined by the same Act.

  5. The population of the Gold Fields.

  6. That of the Seaport Towns.

  7. The distribution of the inhabitants in the Seaport Towns, and the Rural and Mining Districts of the Colony.

  8. Comprises a list of Towns and Villages, the population of which appeared to be of sufficient importance to deserve separate mention. After these follow—

  9. Returns in detail of the Ages of the People in the several Counties.

  10. In the present Electoral Districts.

  11. In the Electoral Provinces for the New Legislative Council ; and

  12. Of those for the New Legislative Assembly.

5.

It is intended that these returns shall be succeeded as early as practicable by a series which will shew the social condition of the people, namely, whether married, unmarried, widowers, or widows, their religion, education, and the country of their birth.

6.

As it is probable that I may be expected to offer some remarks as to the degree of reliance which should be placed on these Census Returns, I would here take leave to observe, that although, as in other countries, notwithstanding the most carefully devised arrangements, omissions may no doubt have occurred, yet, after mature consideration, I have arrived at the conclusion, that taking them altogether, and after making due allowance for such probable omissions, these latter cannot materially affect the general results, and, consequently, that the returns may be received as substantially correct. It is true that numerous complaints of neglect on the part of some of the sub-enumerators have appeared in the public press, but in several instances where the locality alluded to could be traced, it was found upon enquiry either that those complaints had originated in misapprehension—the information required to be given in the schedules supposed to have been neglected, having been, in fact, returned by other parties—or that the schedules, which had in the first instance been accidentally overlooked, had been subsequently recovered.

7.

This opinion of the general fidelity of the returns is much strengthened by applying to them as a rough test the numbers of the population shewn by the Census of 1851, corrected by the subsequent

monthly returns of the Immigration Agent. Thus, the population according to the Census of 1851 was 77,345

The arrivals by sea to 31st December, 185113,892
The arrivals by sea to 31st December, 185294,664
The arrivals by sea to 31st December, 185392,312
The arrivals by sea to 30th April, 185426,779
227,647

DeductmdashDepartures by sea to 31st December, 185231,038
DeductmdashDepartures by sea to 31st December, 185342,443
DeductmdashDepartures by sea to 30th April, 185412,930

138,274
215,619

Accordingly it will be seen that as the population of the Colony on the 2nd March, 1851, was 77,345 persons, and as the excess in the number of immigrants arrived over the number of persons who had departed by sea was 138,274, the population remaining on the 26th April, 1854, would be only 215,619. The Census taken on that day returns the actual number ascertained at 236,798, the difference of 21,179 persons being fairly assignable to an increase arising from undetected arrivals by sea and overland, and from the probable excess of births over deaths during the intervening two years. I may here observe that, of this last element, we have no data on which it is possible to found any safe calculations ; the present system of registration in this Colony having only commenced in 1853.

8.

It would be difficult for a person unacquainted with the subject to form any idea of the obstacles which have to be overcome in a new country in taking the Census of a population irregularly spread over an area of about 90,000 square miles, or about the size of England, Wales, and Ireland united, devoid for the most part of public roads, and traversed in every direction by innumerable tracks and by-ways, and in some parts absolutely impracticable for travelers : a remarkable instance of which was experienced in Gipps' Land, where the sub-enumerator, in his journey from Sale to the neighbourhood of Cape Howe to distribute the Census schedules, was actually compelled to leave the Colony, and to cross over a portion of the territory of New South Wales in order to reach his district. These natural difficulties were in no small degree enhanced by the prejudice which unfortunately existed in the minds of many of the uneducated portion of the community against what was conceived to be an inquisitorial proceeding, and by the unsettled habits of a large body of the people perpetually on the move from one gold field to another by various routes, and whom it was exceedingly difficult to overtake. The absence of recent and complete maps was also much felt.

9.

The Act 17 Victoria, No. 9, for taking an account of the population of the Colony of Victoria, received the Royal Assent on the 1st March, 1854, and the Census was therein directed to be taken on the 26th of April following. It was during this brief interval of eight weeks that the forms of Householder's Schedules were to be prepared and printed, the enumerators to be appointed by the Lieutenant Governor, the sub-enumerators to be selected by those officers and reported for His Excellency's approval, the rates of their remuneration and allowance for travelling expenses to be fixed, and, above all, the boundaries of their respective districts to be clearly defined. This proved to be no easy matter to arrange so as to prevent double returns, or no returns at all being made, in consequence of the absence of definite limits to some of the police districts ; an embarrassment which was further increased by the circumstance of official changes occurring among the police magistrates on the very eve of the day appointed for taking the Census. Before, however, these essential preliminaries could be settled, and the machinery brought into working order, the rains in various parts of the country set in at an earlier period than usual, thus adding considerably to the existing difficulties as well as to the expense to be incurred in the transmission of the blank householders' schedules to the more distant enumerators, and rendering it necessary in some instances to forward them on horseback to their destination. The total cost of this Census may be estimated at about £ 11,000.

10.

Under all circumstances, however, of human affairs, when an energetic determination exists to discharge a public duty, success more or less perfect will ever be found to reward the exertions made to overcome difficulties, and on this occasion the zeal and activity displayed by the various officers employed were eventually attended with the desired result.

11.

The various forms of schedules recently employed in the United Kingdom were adapted by Mr. Archer, Assistant Registrar General, to the circumstances and requirements of the Colonial Census. The Colony was divided into 26 districts, each of which was placed under the charge of an Enumerator. The time allowed was obviously too limited to admit of making enquiries for a reliable selection of these officers from among parties disposed to engage in this service, especially in the bush districts, and no other resource appearing to remain, the Government adopted the course of employing the Police Magistrates. An exception was made in the instance of the City of Melbourne, where it was considered that the Town Clerk, from having official access to the assessment rolls, would have it in his power to exercise a more efficient supervision over the schedules collected by his sub-enumerators. One hundred and ninety-four sub-enumerators were employed ; they were engaged upon the best terms that could be obtained at that time ; the rate of remuneration varying according to the facility or difficulty experienced in finding men and horses, and the nature of the country they had to traverse, whether easy of access, thinly or densely settled, or of a wild and extensive character ; but in many places the services of none but the mounted police could be obtained, except upon such extravagant terms as were quite inad

missible. Endeavours were also made to strengthen what it was easily for seen would be a weak point in this arduous undertaking, by stationing agents upon the main thoroughfares to the gold fields, in order to ascertain the number of travellers, and some of the persons thus employed contrived to obtain not only the numbers but the ages of parties on the road : this success, however, was by no means general.

12.

Although the circumstances and population of the two countries admit of no fair comparison being attempted to be drawn as to the details of the service, it may not be amiss to mention here, that in Great Britain alone, with all its abundant facilities and appliances arising from well-known territorial subdivisions, and its host of union, parochial, and registration officers, all perfectly acquainted with their districts, considerably more than 43,300 persons, besides clerks, messengers, &c., are stated to have been employed in taking the Census of 1851, in addition to the Registrar General's official staff in London. By means of this machinery skillfully directed, a rough summary of the returns was presented to Parliament before the close of the session of 1851 ; but upwards of two years elapsed before the first correct abstract of the numbers of the inhabitants and houses were published, and the series is not yet completed.

13.

Pending the distribution and subsequent collection of the schedules by the sub-enumerators, their correction of errors and omissions by the enumerators, and their final transmission to this office, it became the duty of the Assistant Registrar General (Mr. Archer) and myself, to organise a staff of competent persons for the reduction of the data thus to be obtained, into a tabular form, to provide the requisite books, offices, and materials, and to prescribe the general course of procedure. From a considerable number of eligible candidates, three gentlemen were selected whose acquirements and previous habits appeared to render them qualified to undertake a task requiring no small exercise of discrimination and patient labor. This small party was placed under the charge of Mr. Francis A. Corbett, and I gladly avail myself of this opportunity of bringing under notice the talent and assiduity displayed by that gentleman and his coadjutors. The returns which accompany this report are the result of their protracted labors, and I now proceed to notice some of the more interesting statistical facts which they exhibit.

14.

The total number of persons of all ages ascertained to have been in the Colony of Victoria on the 26th April, 1854, was 236,798, of whom 155,876 were males, and 80,900 females ; there were 22 persons whose sex was not returned.

15.

The great disproportion between the numbers of the sexes, being 193 males to every 100 females, can scarcely fail to attract the attention of the Legislature ; the proportion of the previous Census having been 148 males to 100 females. The result will not be materially affected if we deduct the young people under 15 years of age from the total population, the ages of this class being respectively 30,996 males and 30,383 females. A remarkable exception to the general result occurred at

Belfast and at Portland, where the females outnumbered the males by 15 and 60 respectively ; this was attributable in some measure to recent arrivals of ships with female immigrants.

16.

The ages of the people will be found to be :—From 15 to 45 years, 103,292 males, and 45,403 females ; 45 years and upwards, 12,156 males, and 4,174 females. The ages of 10,272 persons, principally travellers on the gold fields, were not specified. The population under 20 years of age amounted to 39,688 males, and 37,596 females.

17.

It may be useful to those who are engaged in the discussion of the educational question to state that the ages of the children are respectively :—

Males.Females.
Under 5 years12,90113,065
Between 5 and 1010,17010,034
Between 10 and 157,9257,284
Making a total of30,99630,383

18.

The following appears to have been the distribution of the population of the Colony on the 26th April, viz. :—City of Melbourne and seaport towns (Table VI.), 65,251 males, and 45,383 females ; total (including 14 whose sex was not specified), 110,648 persons. On the gold fields, 52,542 males, and 14,152 females ; total (including 3 sex unspecified), 66,697 persons. Population of the inland towns and rural districts, 38,083 males, and 21,365 females ; total (including 5 persons sex unspecified), 59,453 persons.

19.

The population of the City of Melbourne within the boundaries of the six wards (Bourke, Fitz Roy, Gipps', Hotham, La Trobe, and Lonsdale), was returned at 53,235 persons of all ages, of whom 21,096 were females, and 32,134 were males, besides 5 sex unspecified. The metropolis may practically be considered to comprise the inhabitants of Collingwood, Richmond, Prahran, Flemington, and vessels in the Yarra Yarra, which will make the aggregate population of Melbourne and its suburbs amount to 76,565 persons.

20.

The number of inhabitants at Geelong is returned at 20,324 persons, of whom 11,272 were males and 9,043 were females ; there were 9 whose sex was unspecified.

21.

No note appears to have been taken of the aboriginal tribes, with the exception of a very few individuals who were employed on stations, and who are returned accordingly. The estimated number of aborigines is stated to be about 2,500, but no certain information respecting them has been obtained.

22.

Table IV., shewing the population in the Electoral Districts of the Legislative Assembly under the New Constitution Act, presents some

particulars which will be interesting in the consideration of the representative system, when viewed as based on numbers. Table I. also may not be without its value as bearing on the land question.

23.

I venture to express my hope that Table VII., shewing the population of the Towns and Villages of Victoria, will be found acceptable ; it may perhaps serve as the foundation for some future Gazetteer of the Colony, and in the meantime will afford the means of a ready reference as to the Counties and Electoral Districts in which they are situated.

24.

It now only remains for me, in conclusion, in order to make a practical application of the Census, to bring down the enumeration of the people to the latest period, and the following statement will shew the actual population of the Colony at the commencement of the present year, so far as the same can be calculated from the Census of 1854, the Immigration Agent's subsequent returns, and the registers of births and deaths.

Males.Females.Totals.
By the Census Returns there were on the 26th April, 1854155,87680,900236,798

The ascertained population of Victoria on the 1st January, 1855, consisted therefore of 273,792 persons of all ages.

I have the honor to be,

Sir,

Your most obedient humble Servant,

NORMAN CAMPBELL.

Registrar General.

The Honorable,

The Colonial Secretary.

RETURN OF ELECTORAL PROVINCES OF THE LEGISLATIVE COUNCIL, ACCORDING TO 17 VICTORIA, SCHEDULE E.

Population Enumerated 26th April, 1854.

1. CENTRAL PROVINCE.

Boundaries of the Electoral Province.

Commencing at a point on the coast of Port Phillip Bay, which is the south-eastern corner of portion A, in section No. 3, parish of Cut-paw-paw ; bounded on the west by the section line bearing due north as far as the north-eastern corner of section No. 16 ; thence by a road also bearing north to the north-west corner of portion 4, in section No. 21; on the north by a road running east from last-mentioned point to the Saltwater River ; thence by a continuation of said road to the south-west corner of portion 9, in section No. 5, in the parish of Doutta Galla ; thence by the sectional line bearing due east, crossing the Moonee Ponds, the main road to Sydney, and the Merri Creek, which sectional line forms the southern boundaries of portions 91, 90, and 89, in the parish of Jika Jika, as far as the south-east corner of portion 89 aforesaid ; on the east by the sectional line bearing south from the said point in portion 89 to the south-western corner of portion 113, where it strikes the River Yarra Yarra ; again on the north by the said River Yarra Yarra to the north-western corner of portion 59, in the parish of Boroondara ; thence on the east by the western boundary of the said portion 59, till it strikes the road running due south to the Yarra Yarra River ; thence by the said road to the Yarra Yarra River ; by the course of the said river to the north-eastern corner of portion No. 18, in the parish of Prahran ; thence again on the east by a road bearing due south from the last-mentioned point to the south-eastern corner of portion No. 32, east of Elsternwick ; on the south by a road bearing west from the last-mentioned point till it strikes the sea coast ; thence by the line of sea coast crossing the mouth of the said Yarra Yarra River to the point of commencement.

2. SOUTH PROVINCE.

Boundaries of the Electoral Province.

PART OF BOURKE.—

Bounded on the south-west and west by the Werribee River to its source in the Great Dividing Range ; on the north by the Great Dividing Range from the source of the Werribee River to that of the Plenty River ; on the east by the Plenty River from its source to its confluence with the Yarra Yarra ; thence by the Yarra Yarra River upwards to the confluence of the Deep Creek ; thence by the Deep Creek upwards to the point where the main stream commences to run in a north-easterly direction ; thence by a line south two miles fifty-eight chains from the aforesaid bend to Dandenong Creek ; thence by that creek downward to the Curram Swamp ; on the south by the Curram Swamp and Mordialloc Creek to its embouchure at the long beach below Ben-Ben-Gin, and on the remainder of the south by the shores of Port Phillip Bay to the mouth of the Werribee River aforesaid ; excluding the country comprised within the boundaries of the Central Province.

EVELYN.—

Bounded on the west by part of the eastern boundary of the county of Bourke, namely, first by the River Plenty, from its source to the River Yarra Yarra ; thence by the River Yarra Yarra upwards to the confluence of the Deep Creek ; thence by that creek upwards to the range between the Yarra Yarra and the Dandenong Creek ; on the south-east and north by the range forming the basin of the Yarra Yarra.

MORNINGTON.—

Bounded on the north by part of the southern boundary of the county of Evelyn, being the dividing range from the source of the Buneep Buneep River to the head of the Deep Creek ; thence by that creek to the point where the main stream commences to run in a north-west direction ; on the west by a line south two miles fifty-eight chains from the aforesaid bend to Dandenong Creek ; thence by that creek downwards to the Curram Swamp ; by that swamp and the Mordialloc Creek to its embouchure at the long beach below Ben-Ben-Gin ; thence by the shores of Port Phillip Bay to Point Nepean ; on the south-west and south by the sea coast from Point Nepean to Cape Patterson ; and on the east by a line north from Cape Patterson to the Warringrin Range ; thence along the said range in a northerly direction to the north of the Buneep Buneep River, and by that river to its source in the dividing range, including French and Phillip Island and the small islands in Western Port Bay.

3. SOUTH-WESTERN PROVINCE.

Boundaries of the Electoral Province.

GRENVILLE.—

GRANT.—Bounded on the east by the western boundary of the county of Bourke, being the Werribee River from its mouth to its source in the Great Dividing Range; on the north by the Great Dividing Range, extending from the source of the Werribee River to that of the Yarrowee River ; on the west and south-west by the Yarrowee River to its confluence with the Barwon River; thence by the Barwon River upwards to a creek in H. Hopkins's purchased land ; by this creek upwards and a line bearing south-east across the Dividing Range to the head of the Salt Creek two miles forty-eight chains ; thence by the Salt Creek to the sea coast north of Point Roadknight ; on the south by the sea coast ; and on the remainder of the east by the waters of Port Phillip to the mouth of the Werribee River, including the small islands near the channels at the mouth of Port Phillip and those of Geelong Bay.

GRENVILLE.—

Bounded on the west by the eastern boundary of the county of Hampden, namely, a line southerly from Emu Creek to Gnarkeet Ponds ; thence by the Gnarkeet Ponds to Lake Korangamite ; thence by the western shore of that lake to a point east of Lake Pormbeet ; on the south by part of the northern boundary of the county of Heytesbury and the northern boundary of the county of Polwarth, namely, the southern shore of Lake Korangamite ; thence an east line from Lake Korangamite to the north end of Lake Colac ; thence by the north shore of Lake Colac to the point due west from the source of Birregurra Creek ; and from that point by a line east to the source of Birregurra Creek ; thence by that creek downwards to its confluence with the Barwon ; on the east by the River Barwon to its confluence with the Yarrowee River ; thence by the Yarrowee River up to its source in the Great Dividing Range; and on the north by part of the Great Dividing Range to the source of Burrumbeet Creek ; thence by that creek and the southern shores of Lake Burrumbeet to the point where Bailie's Creek leaves the lake ; by Bailie's Creek to its confluence with Emu Creek ; thence by Emu Creek down to the point north of the source of Gnarkeet Ponds aforesaid.

POLWARTH.—

Bounded on the west by the eastern boundary of the county of Heytesbury, namely, the Gellibrand River upwards to its source ; thence by the range to the head of the Pirron-Yalloak Creek ; by this creek to Lake Korangamite ; on the north by the south-eastern shore of Lake Korangamite ; and on the east line from Lake Korangamite to the north end of Lake Colac ; thence by the north shore of Lake Colac to the point due west from the source of the Birregurra Creek ; from that point by a line east to the source of Birregurra Creek ; thence by the Birregurra Creek to its confluence with the River Barwon ; thence following the source of the River Barwon to a creek in H. Hopkins's purchased land ; on the north-east by this creek upwards and a line across the Dividing Range to the head of the Salt Creek bearing south-east two miles forty chains ; thence by the Salt Creek to the sea coast north of Point Roadknight ; and on the south-east and south by the sea coast to the mouth of the Gellibrand River.

4. WESTERN PROVINCE.

Boundaries of the Electoral Province.

RIPON.—

Bounded on the west by the Grampian Range (which divides the waters of the Wimmera and Glenelg Rivers from those of the River Hopkins) to the rocky extremity near Mount Abrupt ; on the south by a line easterly to the source of the first creek which joins the River Hopkins above Wiselaskie's Station on the western side, and by that creek to the River Hopkins ; thence by a line east to Lake Boloke ; thence by the southern shores of Lake Boloke to the mouth of the Prackmingerrin Creek, and by that creek upwards to a point where a great bend of the creek turns northwards ; thence by a line to a point in Emu Creek about one mile below and to the west of the confluence of Broken Creek ; on the south-east and east of Emu Creek to the confluence with Bailie's Creek ; by Bailie's Creek to Lake Burrumbeet, the southern shores of Lake Burrumbeet and Burrumbeet Creek to its source in the Great Dividing Range ; and on the north by the Great Dividing Range to the western boundary aforesaid.

HAMPDEN.—

Bounded on the west by the River Hopkins upwards, from the confluence of the Emu Creek to the point opposite the mouth of the small creek above Wisclaskie's Station, dividing it from the county of Villiers ; on the north by the southern boundary of the county of Ripon, being a line east from the confluence of the creek near Wiselaskie's Station already mentioned to Lake Boloke ; thence by the southern shore of Lake Boloke to the mouth of the Prackmingerrin Creek ; thence by that creek upwards until it reaches a spot where it forms a great bend to the northward, from that point by a line in a south-easterly direction to Emu Creek, about one mile below and westward of the month of Broken Creek ; thence by Emu Creek to the point north of the source of Gnarkeet Ponds ; then on the east by the west boundary of the county of Grenville, viz., first, by a line southerly to the source of Gnarkeet Ponds, then by Gnarkeet Ponds to Lake Korangamite, and thence by the west shore of Lake Korangamite to a point east of Lake Pormbeet ; and on the south by a direct line to the north end of Lake Pormbeet ; and from the north end of Lake Pormbeet to the nearest part of Emu Creek ; and thence by Emu Creek to its confluence with the River Hopkins.

HEYTESBURY.—

Bounded on the north-west and north by part of the eastern boundary of the county of Villiers and the southern boundary of the county of Hampden, being the Hopkins River from its estuary to the confluence of the Emu Creek, and a line easterly to the north end of Lake Burrumbeet ; thence by a line east to Lake Korangamite, by the southern shore of that lake to the mouth of the Pirron-Yalloak Creek ; on the east and south-east by the Pirron-Yalloak Creek to its source ; thence by a range to the head of the Gellibrand River ; by the Gellibrand River to the sea coast ; and on the south-west and west by the sea coast to the estuary of the Hopkins River.

VILLIERS.—

Bounded on the west by a line due south from the Grange Burn to the mouth of the Swamp Creek ; thence by this creek upwards to its source by a line to the head of the western branch of the River Shaw ; thence by the west branch of the River Shaw to the sea ; on the south by the sea to the entrance of the River Hopkins ; on the east by the said River Hopkins to the confluence of the creek above Wiselaskie's Station, and by that creek to its source ; on the north by a line westward from the source of the last-named creek to the rocky extremity of the Grampians, near Mount Abrupt ; thence by the principal range of the Grampians to Mount Sturgeon, and by a line south-westerly to the north-east corner of the county of Normanby at the Grange Burn, including all the islands of Port Fairy.

NORMANBY.—

Bounded on the north by the Grange Burn and Wannon River, until the latter joins the Glenelg River ; on the west by the Glenelg River until it reaches the sea ; on the south by the sea shore to the mouth of the Shaw River ; and on the east by the western branch of the Shaw River to its source ; thence by a line northerly to the source of the Swamp Creek, by that creek to where it empties itself into the Mount Napier Swamp ; and thence by a line due north six miles fifteen chains to the Grange Burn, including the Lawrence and Lady Julia Perey's Islands.

DUNDAS.—

Bounded on the west and north by the Glenelg River upwards from the confluence of the Wannon to its source between the Victoria Range and Grampians, near Mount William ; on the east by the Grampians to its rocky extremity near Mount Abrupt ; thence to Mount Sturgeon and by a line crossing the Wannon River to the north-east corner of the county of Normanby, at the Grange Burn; and on the south by the Grange Burn and the Wannon River to it confluence with the Glenelg.

FOLLETT.—

Bounded on the west by the one hundred and forty-first meridian, being the line dividing the Colony of Victoria from South Australia ; on the south and east by the Glenelg River upwards to its confluence with Power's Creek, and on the north-east and north by Power's Creek to its source ; thence by a line westward to the head of Mosquito Creek, and by that creek to the boundary line.

5. NORTH-WESTERN PROVINCE.

Boundaries of the Electoral Province.

TALBOT.—

Bounded on the north-west and north by the south-western branch of the Loddon River, from its source near Mount Cole to its confluence with the main stream ; thence by the Loddon River upwards to the confluence of Mount Alexander Creek, by this creek to its source under Mount Alexander ; thence by Mount Alexander Range to the head of Myrtle Creek, and by this creek to its confluence with the Coliban River ; on the east by the Coliban River upwards to its source, being part of the western boundary of the county of Dalhousie ; and on the south by the Great Dividing Range to the source of the south-western branch of the Loddon River near Mount Cole.

DALHOUSIE.—

Bounded on the west by the River Coliban, from its source in the Great Dividing Range to its confluence with the Campaspe River, and by the Campaspe River down to the confluence of Mount Ida Creek ; on the north by Mount Ida Creek to its source near Mount Ida, by the Dividing Range to the source of Sandy Creek, and by the Sandy Creek to the Goulburn River ; on the east by the Goulburn River upwards until it joins the Dabyminga Creek, and by that creek to its source in the Dividing Range ; and on the south by the Great Dividing Range.

WIMMERA.—

Bounded on the east by a line from Mount Cole to the source of the Avoca River ; thence by the Avoca River to Lake Bael Bael ; thence by a line due north to the River Murray ; on the north by the River Murray to the South Australian frontier ; on the west by the south Australian frontier south to Mosquito Creek ; on the south by Mosquito Creek to its head ; thence by a line to the source of Power's Creek ; by Power's Creek to its junction with the Glenelg River ; by this river to its source between the Victoria Range and the Grampians near Mount William ; and by the Dividing Range easterly to Mount Cole.

LODDON.—

Bounded on the south by part of the counties of Dalhousie, Talbot, and Ripon, from the Campaspe River to the source of the Avoca River ; on the west by the Avoca River to Lake Bael Bael, and thence by a line due north to the River Murray ; on the north and north-east by the River Murray ; and on the east by the Campaspe River to the point of commencement.

6. EASTERN PROVINCE.

Boundaries of the Electoral Province.

ANGLESEY.—

Bounded on the west by part of the eastern boundary of the county of Dalhousie, namely, from the River Goulburn upwards from the confluence of Hughes's Creek to the confluence of the Dabyminga Creek ; thence by the Dabyminga Creek upwards to its source in the Great Dividing Range ; on the south by the Great Dividing Range to the main source of the River Goulburn ; on the east by the range dividing the waters of the main source of the River Goulburn and Big Rivers from those of Rubicon and Snod-pon-dock Creek northward to Mount Torbrick ; thence by Jerusalem Creek to its confluence with the River Goulburn ; thence by the River Goulburn downwards to its confluence with the Devil's River ; thence by the Devil's River and its north-west arm to the dividing range between the last named arm and Septimus Creek ; and on the north by that range to the source of Hughes's Creek ; thence by Hughes's Creek down to its confluence with the River Goulburn.

RODNEY.—

Commencing at the confluence of the Rivers Campaspe and Coliban ; thence by a line south-easterly to the Mcivor or Patterson's Creek, above John Hunter Patterson's Sheep Station ; thence by a line north-easterly to the confluence of Hughes's Creek with the River Goulburn, and by that river to the Murray ; thence by the River Murray to its confluence with the River Campaspe, and by the River Campaspe upwards to the confluence of the Rivers Campaspe and Coliban aforesaid.

MURRAY.—

Bounded on the south and west by the counties of Evelyn and Anglesey and the River Goulburn to its Junction with the Murray ; on the north and north-east by the River Murray ; and on the south-east by the Dividing Range (Alps).

GIPPS' LAND.—

Bounded on the south and east by the sea ; on the north by a line running in a westerly direction from Cape Howe to the source of the nearest tributary of the Murray and the Australian Alps ; again, on the west by the Alps and the counties of Evelyn and Mornington.

29. ELECTORAL DISTRICT OF EVELYN AND MORNINGTON.

Boundaries of the Electoral District.

EVELYN.—

Bounded on the west by part of the eastern boundary of the county of Bourke—that is to say, by the River Plenty from its source to the River Yarra Yarra ; thence by the River Yarra Yarra to the confluence of the Deep Creek ; thence by that creek to the range between the River Yarra Yarra and the Dandenong Creek ; on the south-east and north by the range forming the basin of the River Yarra Yarra.

MORNINGTON.—

Bounded on the north by part of the southern boundary of the county of Evelyn, being the Dividing Range from the source of the River Buneep Buneep to the source of the Deep Creek ; thence by that creek and a line south two miles fifty-eight chains from that creek to the Dandenong Creek ; thence by that creek to the Carrum Swamp ; by that swamp and the Mordialloc Creek to its mouth at the long beach below Ben-Ben-Gin ; thence by the shores of Port Phillip Bay to Point Nepean ; on the south-west and south by the sea coast from Point Nepean to Cape Patterson ; on the east by a line north from Cape Patterson to the Warringria Range ; thence along the said range in a northerly direction to the mouth of the River Buneep Buneep, and by that river to its source in the Dividing Range, including French and Phillip Islands and the small islands in Western Port Bay.

30. ELECTORAL DISTRICT OF ANGLESEY.

Boundaries of the Electoral District.

PART OF DALHOUSIE.—

Commencing at the junction of the Rivers Campaspe and Coliban ; thence by a line south-easterly to the source of the McIvor or Paterson's Creek ; thence by a line north-east to the confluence of Hughes's Creek with the River Goulburn ; on the east by the River Goulburn until it joins the Dabyminga Creek ; by that creek to its source in the Dividing Range ; on the south by the Dividing Range to the source of the River Coliban ; and on the west by the last-mentioned river to its junction with the River Campaspe, being the commencing point, excepting the country included in the Electoral Districts of the Kyneton Boroughs and of Kilmore.

ANGLESEY.—

Bounded on the west by part of the eastern boundary of the county of Dalhousie, namely, from the River Goulburn from the confluence of Hughes's Creek to the confluence of Dabyminga Creek ; thence by Dabyminga Creek to its source in the Great Dividing Range ; on the south by the Great Dividing Range to the main source of the River Goulburn ; on the east by the range dividing the waters of the main source of the Goulburn and Big Rivers from those of the Rubicon and Snod-pon-dock Creek northwards to Mount Torbrick ; thence by Jerusalem Creek to its confluence with the River Goulburn ; thence by the River Goulburn to the confluence of the River Delatite ; thence by the River Delatite and its north-west arm to the Dividing Range between the last-named arm and Septimus Creek ; and on the north by that range to the source of Hughes's Creek ; and thence by Hughes's Creek to its confluence with the River Goulburn, excepting the country included in the Borough of Seymour.

34. ELECTORAL DISTRICT OF POLWARTH, RIPON, HAMPDEN, AND SOUTH GRENVILLE.

Boundaries of the Electoral District.

POLWARTH.—

Bounded on the west by the River Gellibrand upwards to its source ; thence by the range to the source of the Pirron Yaloak Creek, by this creek to Lake Korangamite ; on the north by the south-eastern shore of Lake Korangamite and an east line from Lake Korangamite to the north of Lake Colac ; thence by the north shore of Lake Colac to the point west from the source of the Birregurra Creek, from that point by a line east to the source of the Birregurra Creek ; thence by the Birregurra Creek to its confluence with the River Barwon ; thence following the course of the River Barwon to Hopkins's Creek ; on the north-east by this creek and a line across the Dividing Range to the source of the Salt Creek south-east two miles forty-eight chains ; thence by the Salt Creek to the sea coast north of Point Roadknight ; and on the south-east and south by the sea coast to the mouth of the River Gellibrand, excepting the country included in the Electoral District of Colac.

RIPON.—

Bounded on the west by the Grampian Range, dividing the waters of the Rivers Wimmera and Glenelg from those of the River Hopkins to its base near Mount Abrupt ; on the south by a line easterly to the source of Wyselaskie's Creek, and by that creek to the River Hopkins ; thence by a line east to Lake Boloke ; thence by the southern shores of Lake Boloke to the mouth of the Brackmingerrin Creek, and by that creek to the point nearest to Emu Creek ; thence by a line east to a point in Emu Creek one mile to the west of its confluence with Broken Creek ; on the south-east and east by Emu Creek to its confluence with Bailie's Creek ; by Bailie's Creek to Lake Burrumbeet ; by the southern shores of Lake Burrumbeet and Burrumbeet Creek to its source in the Great Dividing Range ; and on the north by the Great Dividing Range to the western boundary aforesaid.

HAMPDEN.—

Bounded on the west by the River Hopkins ; on the north by the southern boundary of the county of Ripon ; on the east by a line southerly to the source of Gnarkeet Ponds ; thence by Gnarkeet Ponds to Lake Korangamite, and thence by the west shore of Lake Korangamite to a point east of Lake Pormbeet, and from the north end of Lake Pormbeet to the nearest part of Emu Creek, and thence by Emu Creek to its confluence with the River Hopkins.

SOUTH GRENVILLE.—

Bounded on the north by the main road between Portland and Geelong, from its intersection with the River Yarrowee to the Gnarkeet Ponds ; on the west by the Gnarkeet Ponds to Lake Korangamite ; thence by the western shores of that lake to a point east of Pormbeet ; on the south by the southern shore of Lake Korangamite ; thence by a line east from Lake Korangamite to the north shore of Lake Colac ; thence by the north shore of Lake Colac to a point west from the Birregurra Creek, and from that point by a line east to the source of the Birregurra Creek, by that creek to its confluence with the Barwon ; and on the east by the Rivers Barwon and Yarrowee to the commencing point.

ALPHABETICAL INDEX

REPORT.

Registrar General's Office,

November 22nd, 1855.

SIR,

I have the honor of submitting the accompanying Abstract of the Census Returns of April, 1854, shewing the numbers of the various Religious Denominations of the People of Victoria, so far as they were ascertained at that date.

2.

The more detailed Returns which accompany this Abstract will be found to present an interesting view of the distribution of the several denominations throughout the Counties, Pastoral Districts, Parishes, and Towns in the Colony ; and it may be observed, on a careful examination, that the relative proportion between the different religious bodies varies considerably in the towns, as compared with the numbers in the purely rural districts.

3.

The labor and difficulty which, even under ordinary circumstances, necessarily attend the correct preparation of such returns, owing to the majority of people being unaccustomed to filling up official documents, have been greatly increased on the present occasion through the ignorance or negligence often evinced by householders to whom the schedules were delivered, as well as by the apparent unwillingness of many to state their religious opinions with distinctness, to which must be added the frequent use of terms of general or lax signification, such as "Catholic," "Protestant," "Presbyterian," "Israelite," "Freethinker," and others of a similar nature. In all doubtful and unspecified cases the utmost pains have been taken to place the inmates of each dwelling, as far as possible, under their proper designation, by a careful comparison with the answers given under other headings ; but where this classification was not clearly warranted the parties have been suffered to remain in the doubtful classes under which they were returned. I trust, however, that on the occasion of the next Census, sufficient time being allowed for a careful selection of sub-enumerators, and for their instruction as to the nature and extent of their duties, much of this ambiguity may be obviated, by requiring those officers to examine and rectify on the spot the defective schedules.

4.

It will be seen from the accompanying Abstracts (Table C.) that the relative numerical proportions of the several religious bodies have altered considerably since the Census of 1851. This alteration may in some measure be accounted for by the circumstance of the larger portion of the recent immigration, induced by the attraction of the gold fields, having been derived from England and Wales, and from the Highlands of Scotland.

5.

The numbers of the principal denominations, according to each of these Censuses, may be thus briefly stated :—

Denomination.1851.1854.
Church of England37,433108002*
Roman Catholic Church18,01445,111
Churches of Scotland and Presbyterians11,60842,317
Wesleyan Methodists4,98815,284
Other Protestants4,33118,234
[* In the Summary Tables the "Protestants" have been included with the members of the Church of England, and the "Catholics" with those of the Roman Catholic Church, because the corrections made in the schedules at the instance of the sub-enumerators, have almost invariably shewn that the persons using those terms have meant to designate those respective churches. Presbyterians, in describing their religion, seldom called themselves Protestants ; and members of the other Protestant denominations were generally very precise in indicating the particular body to which they belonged.]

6.

The absolute increase in each of these religious bodies during the interval of three years has been :—

Denomination.Persons.
Church of England70,569
Roman Catholic Church27,097
Presbyterians30,709
Wesleyan Methodists10,296
Other Protestants13,921

7.

Of the 42,317 Presbyterians in the Colony a considerable proportion (12,033) have returned themselves as belonging to the Free Church of Scotland, and 2,841 to the United Presbyterian Church. It has been objected to these figures by ministers of the latter body that "the number returned as United Presbyterians is incorrect, inasmuch as no special heading having been assigned in the schedules to this branch of the Presbyterian Church, parties belonging to it must, necessarily, have classified themselves with some of the other divisions of the Presbyterians or Protestant denominations, or have been at the trouble of writing out their own special designation ; and, further, that as the ministers belonging to the three divisions of the Presbyterian Church in Victoria are very nearly equal in number, it may be supposed that no great disparity exists between the numbers of their several adherents."

8.

No means exist by which the value of these objections can be tested : they are matters of opinion or conjecture. But I may remark that members of the various denominations, whether mentioned or not in the instructions for filling up the column for religion, were all under the necessity of writing out their special designation in full ; and there does not appear to be any greater trouble in writing " United Presbyterian," than "Church of Scotland," or "Free Church of Scotland". Moreover, in the first line of the heading " Religion," it was expressly requested that persons should state clearly the religious denomination to which they belonged ; and it appears that 2,841 members of the United Presbyterian Church understood and responded to this call. Considering, too, the surprising extent of the movement which has taken place of late years among the Presbyterians of Scotland, the generally reflecting habits of that people, and the deep interest which they have ever displayed in matters connected with their religion, I may perhaps be permitted to express a doubt whether the United Presbyterians have to any great extent designated themselves members either of the Church of Scotland or of the

Free Church. That many of them may, from the absence of a specific mention of their body in a printed heading, have returned themselves simply as Presbyterians, is, however, very probable ; but it must, also, be remembered that there are large numbers of Presbyterians in England, Ireland, and other parts of the world, who no doubt have their representatives here, and who form no portion of either of the divisions alluded to.

9.

The Independents or Congregationalists are returned at 7,709 ; the members of the Baptist Persuasion at 4,724 ; the Lutherans, 3,014 ; the Unitarians, 1,180 ; the Society of Friends, 221 ; and of the "Catholic and Apostolic" Church, or Irvingites, it may be remarked that, although numbering but 75, they are organized under the rule of a Bishop resident in the Colony.

10.

The Jews have increased from 304 in the year 1851, to 1,547 in the year 1854 ; but I should observe, that owing to ambiguity in the mode in which many of the Census Schedules have been filled, it is a matter of doubt whether their number has not been over-stated in the Returns. There appear to be but two Rabbis in the Colony.

11.

The Mormons, or Latter-Day Saints, are returned at 132 ; the Mahomedans and Pagans at 3,009 ; and the number of persons who profess to be of no religion, is stated to be 805.

12.

This Report would, I conceive, afford a very incomplete and unsatisfactory synopsis of the Religious Statistics of the Colony, were it not accompanied by some information as to the provision which has been made for Public Worship, by the various denominations,up to the present date.With this object, I have endeavored to collect, from authentic sources, materials for a comparative statement, which will, doubtless, prove acceptable to a great majority of the community ; and I take this opportunity of recording my thanks to the ministers of all denominations for the readiness with which they have co-operated with me in my attempt to obtain some general view of the present position of the Christian Churches in Victoria. The following Table shews, in a condensed and convenient form, the result of my enquiries :—

Denomination.Churches.Schools and Temporary Places of Worship.Total Places of Worship.Ministers.Lay Readers, Lay Preachers, and Mission Agents.Total of Clergymen and Lay Assistants.
Church of England19719048856
* Roman Catholic Church345483535
Presbyterians :—
Synod of Victoria16*541446
Free Church61318
United Presbyterians19*14
Wesleyans21*2620169194
Primitive Methodists2*2
Wesleyan Methodist Association2*2
Bible Christians11
Independents16*1616117
Baptists5*555
Evangelical Lutherans3*333
Unitarians1111
Society of Friends11
Total115129244179178357
[* ROMAN CATHOLIC CHURCHES.—The figures given above do not include the various out-stations, visited monthly by the Country Preists, where Divine Worship is held, and the Sacraments administered, as in temporary places of worship.] [In the case of those numbers marked with asterisks (*) the Returns do not mention how many are Churches, and how many are only temporary erections used as Churches.]

13.

Thus it appears that the proportion which the number of places of worship bears at present to the members of each denomination, as it stood in April, 1854, is as follows, viz :—Church of England, 1 place of worship to every 1,200 persons ; Roman Catholics, 1 to 940 persons ; Presbyterians, 1 to 783 persons ; Wesleyans, 1 to 588 persons ; Independents, 1 to 482 persons ; Baptists, 1 to 945 persons ; Lutherans, 1 to 1,005 persons. It should, however, be observed, that these proportions give a very imperfect idea of the actual provision made for the spiritual wants of the people, because the accommodation afforded by places of worship is dependent not only on their size, but on the number of daily services held in each. The recording of such facts may, however, prove useful for comparison at future periods.

I have the honor to be,

Sir,

Your most obedient servant,

NORMAN CAMPBELL,

Registrar General.

To the Honorable

The Colonial Secretary.

Note.—The Census Returns of 1831 do not state what denominations are included under the head of "Other Persussions." In the returns for 1854 the only bodies to which the term appears applicable are the Greek Church, the Mormons, and the Freethinkers. The former Cenusus Tables do not give any persons as being unspecified. In the earlier enumerations of the numbers of each denomination in these colonies, it appears to have been the custom to assume that all persons whose religion was not specified were members of the Church of England. (See Lang's History of New South Wales.) it is, however, possible that in compiling the Census of 1857, the unspecified were divided amongst the various sects according to the proportion which each here to the total of all religious in the complete returns. This does not appear to be a correct proceeding, because it is evident that many have intentionally omitted to state their religion, owing no doubt to the adoption of opinions not in accordance with the doctrines of any recognised religions body. For this reason it has not been thought proper in the present Census to make any such division of the unspecified, unless in the case of the migratory population, who, it may be presumed, are unspecified merely because they could not be afforded the opportunity of stating their religion.

RODNEY.—In the first part of these Returns, by a clerical error, the lines of figures were transposed, and those representing the numbers and ages of the digging population substituted for the pastoral. SHIPPING.—H.M.S.Electrais included withOther Vessels,under which heading are also included the vessels in all other ports besides those in Hobson's Bay and Melbourne. The HulkSacramento,in Corio Bay, is included with the other Penal Hulks.

TRAVELLERS.—The estimated number of travellers and prospectors on the Gold Fields are divided between the different religions according to the proportion which each sect bears to the total enumerated population.

TheEnumerated Travellersgiven above are those who filled schedules for the Sub-Enumerators at their Encampments. Besides these there were 1023 persons counted or reported as having passed different stations. The latter are included with theComputed,for the purpose of estimating the proportion of them belonging to each religion.

PRESENTED TO BOTH HOUSES OF PARLIAMENT BY HIS EXCELLENCY'S COMMAND.

BY AUTHORITY:

JOHN FERRES, GOVERNMENT PRINTER, MELBOURNE.

CLASSIFICATION.—In all classifications of industrial pursuits, the grouping must be to a certain extent arbitray, and cannot always be perfectly consistent ; inasmuch as some occupations embrace more than one class, particularly where the population is sparse. The order adopted in the Censuses of the United Kingdom has been followed in these Tables as closely as the different between the circumstances of the two countries admitted.

The Table may be read thus :—The total number of Males under 15 years was 30,906, of whom 30,204 had no occupation or were receiving education, leaving 792 in regular employment. Deducting those 792 boys from 120, 697, the total of Males of all pursuits, we find that 119,905 was the number of 15 years of age and upwards who were engaged in actual occupation. Of the 2590, whose pursuits were not specified or who were unemployed, a considerable portion were lads over 15 years of age, some of whom were attending school or receiving tution.
